\par
Digital government policies in the West tend to turn their attention to user-centered design principles. In the United Kingdom, the Government Digital Service (GDS) proclaims, ``users \dots{} are at the centre of everything we do,''\href{http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.5325/jinfopoli.6.2016.0436\#r022}{\textsuperscript{22}}~while in the United States, a ```customer centric' approach influences the creation, management and presentation of government information.''\href{http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.5325/jinfopoli.6.2016.0436\#r023}{\textsuperscript{23}}~The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) says state services should look to ``re-organise themselves around user expectations, needs and associated requirements, rather than their own internal logic and needs.''\href{http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.5325/jinfopoli.6.2016.0436\#r024}{\textsuperscript{24}}~These are different policy responses not least in their political orientation to citizenship, but they share a determination to configure their services for everybody\textemdash citizens, publics, and customers (internal and external to government)\textemdash via commitments to accessibility of information platforms and openness of processes.
