\par
"Interest has a complex, interdisciplinary history. There is long standing debate as to whether interest is an emotion or a non-emotional aspect of attention or motivation (Silvia, 2006), and whether it is distinct from curiosity (Silvia, 2006), choice, locus of control, and volition (Flowerday, Schraw \& Stevens, 2004).  In addition to the challenge of disentangling interest from other constructs, there is also the question of whether interest is an individual difference, or triggered by a particular situation (Flowerday et al., 2004; Silvia, 2006). What is more, how interest informs outcomes such as positive affect, engagement and learning is largely inconclusive (Flowerday et al., 2004). Interest is salient to many areas of information interaction, including online news (Arapakis et. al., 2014), social media (Berger \& Milkman, 2013), and interactive information retrieval (IIR) (Glassey \& Azzopardi, 2011; Ruthven, Ballie, \& Elsweiler, 2007; van der Sluis et al., 2014). Studies have investigated content sentiment and polarity to understand the relationship between affect, interest, enjoyment, and focused attention (Arapakis et al., 2014) or social media virality (Berger \& Milkman, 2013). The ability to monitor and support searchers' interests has implications for designing information systems (Glassey \& Azzopardi, \{This is the space reserved for copyright notices.] ASIST 2016, October 14-18, 2016, Copenhagen, Denmark. [Author Retains Copyright.  Insert personal or institutional copyright notice here.] iSchool, University of British Columbia Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada jocelyn.d.mckay@gmail.com 2011) and constructing experimental search tasks (Ruthven et al., 2007). Thus, the question of what makes content interesting has implications for understanding user psychology, as well as system and experimental design." (\vphantom\}\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_R8HPYEDF/1}{O'Brien and McKay 2016:1})
\par
"Arapakis et al. (2014) found that self-reported interest fostered engagement in online news interactions, and influenced readers' degree of focused attention and positive affect. McCay-Peet, Lalmas and Navalpakkum (2012) manipulated the visual saliency of task-relevant or irrelevant information to influence task performance efficiency. Yet some participants were distracted by "offtopic" content they found interesting. These studies demonstrate the role of individual differences in interest, and question the potential to evoke situational interest, on which many IIR studies may depend." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_R8HPYEDF/1}{O'Brien and McKay 2016:1})
\par
"Thus, it is unclear if interest is a product of prior knowledge or other innate factors, and if it can be engendered when IIR studies do not involve content selected by participants or informed by their prior knowledge. In this paper, we examined user interest, in the absence of choice, and its relationship to story content and its presentation in order to better understand what makes online news content interesting, and people's behavioral intentions as a result of online news interactions" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_R8HPYEDF/2}{O'Brien and McKay 2016:2})
