  url = {http://www.emeraldinsight.com/doi/10.1108/OIR-01-2014-0008},
  urldate = {2016-11-07},
  abstract = {The Web is an increasingly important component of promotional strategy for many organizations. To date, most advertising research has focused on banner ads. In the present study, home pages as promotional vehicles are evaluated. Specifically, we examine the influence of perceived home page complexity on communication effectiveness, as measured by attention to the home page, attitude toward the home page, attitude toward the company, and purchase intent. Qualitative research is used to identify important factors that appear to influence perceptions of home page complexity, including home page length, number of graphics, number of links, amount of text, and use of animation. A pretest experiment further aided in the selection of appropriate factors and factor levels to manipulate in a subsequent, main experiment. The findings in the main experiment suggest that consumers respond more favorably toward home pages that fall in a moderate range of perceived complexity.},
  langid = {english},
  language = {en},
  keywords = {engagement,Engagement,length,Length / Landing pages},
  annotation = {00000},
  note = {\textbf{Yellow Annotations (10/14/2017, 9:39:17 PM)}
\par
"Abstract Purpose - The purpose of this paper is to develop a research model that examines the effect of information overload and information disorganisation upon customers' perceived risk and purchase intention online in a single integrative model. In addition the paper investigates whether internet experience moderates these relationships. Design/methodology/approach - To achieve the paper's objectives an experiment that involved visiting the ten most visited e-commerce web sites in Spain was conducted. Hypotheses were tested by using structural equation modelling on a data set of 1,396 online shopping customers. Findings - The results suggest a positive relationship between information overload and customer purchase intention and that internet experience reinforces this positive effect. Moreover the results confirm that the relationship between information disorganisation and customer purchase intention is not significant and that internet experience does not moderate the relationship. The findings also indicate that perceived risk mediates the relationship between information overload and information disorganisation on customer purchase intention. Originality/value - This work contributes to the literature by exploring the phenomenon of information overload and information disorganisation upon customers' perceived risk and purchase intention in the e-commerce environment as well as the moderating effect of internet experience on these relationships in a single integrative model. The main conclusions of this investigation can be valuable to organisations that implement or intend to implement e-commerce. Keywords e-commerce, Purchase intention, Information overload, Perceived risk, Information disorganization Paper type Research paper" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/2}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:544})
\par
"Academics and practitioners widely acknowledge that conducting transactions through a virtual medium is radically different from shopping offline (Molina-Castillo et al., 2012)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/2}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:544})
\par
"and customers have more control over the information they seek (Vila and Kurster, 2011). Nonetheless the internet's ability to host large amounts of information may produce information overload and affect consumer behaviour (Gurrea et al., 2013; Zha et al., 2013). This phenomenon occurs when consumers are provided with too much information in a limited amount of time, such that it exceeds their processing limits (Eppler and Mengis, 2004; Jackson and Farzaneh, 2012). The problem of information overload is a significant one for contemporary knowledge-intensive organisations as well because it can adversely affect productivity, decision making, and employee morale (Whelan and Teigland, 2013). A large number of studies have analysed the relationships between information overload, information processing, and decision quality at the individual level. Inconsistent results in the above-mentioned relationships have been found when consumers are conducting their purchases online. Several studies (e.g. Chen et al., 2009; Sicilia and Ruiz, 2010) found negative effects from online information overload, while others (e.g. Huang, 2000; Huang et al., 2013) obtained opposite results. These inconsistent findings have been attributed to different operationalisations of information overload and also to the choice of decision quality as the dependent variable (Chen et al., 2009). In addition conclusions regarding information overload in traditional stores may not be extrapolated to the online medium and this issue requires further research." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/3}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:545})
\par
"Another issue that may have major effects on consumer behaviour is the organisation of the information display (De Andres et al., 2010). How the information is structured or organised on the web site may determine its success (Lurie, 2004), since disorientation is the most common navigation problem in hypertext systems (Ruttun and Macredie, 2012) and may cause cognitive overload. Hypertext creates a web of connections and offers a very powerful way of organising and accessing a large body of information. Although text readers use their whole cognitive ability to understand information, web readers need to use their cognitive ability not only for that but also to make decisions regarding the navigation of the web (Yu and Roh, 2002). Moreover excessive search complexity makes it difficult for customers to locate the needed information, thus negatively affecting customers' decision quality (Zha et al., 2013)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/3}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:545})
\par
"Our study lies in the last process of information management: information dissemination. More specifically it assesses the effect of information overload and information disorganisation upon perceived risk and consumers' purchase intention to buy a product via the internet. The following subsections emphasise specific literature on this subject and develop the research hypotheses." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/4}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:546})
\par
"Another theoretical framework used in this paper is Vessey's (1994) cognitive fit theory. According to this perspective, how the information is presented to an individual will affect their performance in a given task and their decision making (Vessey, 1994). In an online context the final decision to be made deals with the purchase of products or services. This study analyses the effect of two features of information presentation (information overload and information disorganisation) on online purchase intention." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/4}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:546})
\par
"Although there is no universally agreed definition of information overload (Jackson and Farzaneh, 2012), we agree with the literature that it usually refers to the notion of receiving too much information at any given time such that it exceeds the processing limits (Eppler and Mengis, 2004; Jackson and Farzaneh, 2012; Whelan and Teigland, 2013). The relationship between information load and information processing is usually described as an inverted U curve. That is, information processing increases when the decision maker is subjected to information underload, while it decreases when they are experiencing information overload (Jacoby et al., 1974). Since decision quality is positively associated with information processing, the relationship between information load and decision quality has been considered as an inverted U curve as well. However, several studies have produced mixed results regarding the effects of information load and decision quality" (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/4}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:546})
\par
"How the information is structured on the web site is another important issue when 546 selling products or services online. In contrast to offline customers, online customers use their cognitive ability not only to understand information but also to navigate through the web (Yu and Roh, 2002). Therefore, although how the information is organised on the web site is independent from its meaning, it has important implications for information processing which, in turn, may influence decision quality (Lurie, 2004)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/5}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:547})
