\par
"As will become clear in the discussion section, this study provides recommendations to managers on what type of information (load vs disorganisation) is more important to increase customer purchase intention." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/13}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:555})
\par
"Previous literature in conventional retail environments found inconsistent results for the relationship between the amount of information and decision quality. Initial research confirmed an inverted U relationship (Jacoby et al., 1974; Scammon, 1977), while later studies found no decrease in decision quality as the information load increased (Keller and Staelin, 1989; Muller, 1984). These inconsistent findings have been attributed to different operationalisations of information overload (Chen et al., 2009) and to the fact that they did not consider context factors. With regard to the internet medium, although several studies suggested that information overload may encourage online transactions (Huang, 2000; Huang et al., 2013), the majority of research found that an excess of information results in a lack of attention towards purchasing online (e.g. Chen et al., 2009; Sicilia and Ruiz, 2010) and that online experience reduces information overload (Chen et al., 2009). Our findings suggest a positive relationship between information overload and customer purchase intention. This is in line with the expectations of Huang (2000)." (\href{zotero://open-pdf/0_KZLN367W/13}{Soto-Acosta et al 2014:555})
